<!-- Generated by Pandoc using pretext.lua -->
<worksheet>
  <title>Evaluating and Revising Proofs</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Foundations of Mathematics</alert>
    </p>
  </introduction>


	<p>
		Here are some attempted proofs, adapted by a colleague from past FOM student answers, of the following statement:
	</p>

	<blockquote>
			<p>
		Suppose <m>n</m> is a positive integer. If <m>n^2</m> is a multiple of <m>3</m>, then <m>n</m> is a multiple of <m>3</m>.
	</p>
	</blockquote>

	<p>
		For each of the following proofs:
	</p>

	<p><ul>
		<li>
			<p>
				Read through the proof line by line. Does each line follow from a known mathematical fact or from previous lines?
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Decide whether it is a valid proof. Why do you think it is valid or invalid?
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Grade the proof on a scale from <m>1</m> (does not verify the statement at all) to <m>5</m> (a completely clear, convincing, and logically sound argument).
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				What advice would you give the proof writer on how to change the proof?
			</p>
		</li>

	</ul></p>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				Let <m>n</m> be an integer such that <m>n^2=3x</m> where <m>x</m> is an integer. Then <m>3 | n^2</m>. Since <m>n^2 = 3x</m>, <m>nn = 3x</m>. Thus <m>3 | n</m>. Therefore if <m>n^2</m> is a multiple of 3, then <m>n</m> is a multiple of 3.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Assume that <m>n^2</m> is an odd positive integer that is divisible by 3. That is <m>n^2 = (3n+1)^2 = 9n^2 + 6n +1 = 3n(n+2)+1</m>. Therefore, <m>n^2</m> is divisible by 3. Assume that <m>n^2</m> is even and a multiple of 3. That is, <m>n^2 = (3n)^2 = 9n^2 = 3n(3n)</m>. Therefore, <m>n^2</m> is a multiple of 3. If we factor <m>n^2 = 9n^2</m>, we get <m>3n(3n)</m>, which means that <m>n</m> is a multiple of 3.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer such that <m>n^2</m> is a multiple of 3. Then <m>n=3m</m> where <m>m \in {\bf Z}</m>. So <m>n^2 = (3m)^2 = 9 m^2 = 3 (3m^2).</m> This breaks down into <m>3m</m> times <m>3m</m> which shows that <m>m</m> is a multiple of 3.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Suppose <m>n</m> is not a multiple of 3. We will let <m>3k</m> be a positive integer that is a multiple of 3, so that <m>3k+1</m> and <m>3k+2</m> are integers that are not multiples of 3. Now <m>n^2 = (3k+1)^2 = 9k^2 + 6k +1 = 3(3k^2+2k) + 1</m>. Since <m>3(3k^2+2k)</m> is a multiple of 3, <m>3(3k^2+2k)+1</m> is not. For the other case, <m>n^2 = (3k+2)^2 = 9k^2 + 12k +4 = 3(3k^2+4k+1) + 1</m>, which is not a multiple of 3.
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>

</worksheet>
